{{Infobox magazine | image_file = Biblical Archaeology Review.jpg | category = [[Archaeology]] | publisher = [[Biblical Archaeology Society]] | editor = Robert R. Cargill | country = United States | based = [[Washington, D.C.]] | frequency = Bimonthly | founded = 1975 | website = {{URL|http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/magazine/}} | issn = 0098-9444 }} '''''Biblical Archaeology Review''''' is a bi-monthly [[magazine]] sometimes referred to as '''BAR''' that seeks to connect the academic study of [[archaeology]] to a broad general audience seeking to understand the world of the [[Bible]] and the Near and Middle East (Syro-Palestine and the [[Levant]]). Since its first issue in 1975,<ref name=Reiss>{{cite news|last1=Reiss|first1=Jana K.|title='Biblical Archaeology Review' Celebrates 40 Years with Retrospective Book|publisher=[[Publishers Weekly]]|date=11 May 2015}}</ref> ''Biblical Archaeology Review'' has covered the latest discoveries and controversies in the archaeology of [[Israel]], [[Turkey]], [[Jordan]] and the surrounding regions as well as the newest scholarly insights into both the [[Hebrew Bible]] and the [[New Testament]]. The magazine is published by the [[Nondenominational Christianity|nondenominational]] and [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] [[Biblical Archaeology Society]] and [[Editor-in-chief|editor]] Robert Cargill.{{citation needed|date=March 2013}}
From its founding in 1975 until 2017, the editor in chief was [[Hershel Shanks]]. After Shanks' retirement at the end of 2017, Robert R. Cargill was selected to be the editor of the publication.
The society also published ''[[Bible Review]]'' (1985–2005) and ''Archaeology Odyssey'', which merged with ''Biblical Archaeology Review'' after 2005.
